# Feature Sliced Design (within modules)

## Relationship to Modular Architecture

This rule is the inner layer of the architecture defined in **modular-architecture**.

- **Module** = domain boundary (e.g. `auth`, `payment`)
- **Feature** = user-facing capability within that domain (e.g. `login`, `reset-password`, `two-factor`)

Every piece of code inside a module belongs to a feature. There is no "module-level" loose code.

## Caminhos

Prefira `src/modules/` neste repositório (alias `@/*` → `./src/*`).

## Directory Structure

```
modules/
  auth/
    features/
      login/
        sessions/         # hook + presentation pairs — ver regra session-architecture
          LoginSession/
            LoginSession.tsx
          LoginForm/
            useLoginForm.ts
            LoginForm.tsx
        services/
        store/
        types/
        utils/
        index.ts
      reset-password/
        sessions/
          ...
        services/
        types/
        index.ts
    components/
    hooks/
    services/
    store/
    types/
    index.ts
```

## Rules

### 1. Every user-facing capability is a feature
- A feature maps to something a user can do: `login`, `reset-password`, `view-invoice`, `apply-coupon`.
- Name features after the action or capability, not after technical concerns (`form`, `modal`, `handler`).
- Features live inside `modules/<domain>/features/<feature-name>/`.

### 2. Feature has its own layers
Each feature folder contains only the layers it needs:

| Layer | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `sessions/` | Hook + presentation pairs — all UI for this feature (see **session-architecture**) |
| `services/` | API calls / data-fetching specific to this feature |
| `store/` | Local or ephemeral state owned by this feature |
| `types/` | TypeScript types used only within this feature |
| `utils/` | Pure functions used only within this feature |
| `index.ts` | Assembles sessions into the final page and exports it — no barrel re-exports |

### 2a. Type promotion rule
A type starts in the feature that first needs it. Promote it as soon as it crosses a boundary:

| Type scope | Where it lives |
|---|---|
| Used by exactly one feature | `features/<feature>/types/` |
| Used by two or more features of the same module | `modules/<domain>/types/` |
| Used by two or more modules | `shared/types/` — only if it has no domain-specific logic |

**Never duplicate a type.** If a second feature needs a type that already exists in `features/<feature>/types/`, do not copy it — promote it immediately to `modules/<domain>/types/` and update both features to import from there.

There is no `components/` or `hooks/` folder inside a feature. Components live in `sessions/` as hook/presentation pairs. Hooks live as `use<Name>.ts` files co-located inside the session folder they serve.

Omit layers that are not needed — do not create empty folders.

### 3. Feature `index.ts` assembles and exports the page
- The feature `index.ts` composes sessions into the final page component and exports it.
- It imports sessions directly by file path — no barrel re-exports of raw sessions or hooks.
- The module's own code may only import from `features/<feature>/index.ts`, never from internal paths.

### 4. Features do not import from sibling features
- `features/reset-password` must not import from `features/login`.
- If two features share something, that something is promoted to the module-level layer (`modules/<domain>/components/`, `hooks/`, `services/`, `types/`).

### 5. Module-level layers are for intra-module sharing only
- `modules/<domain>/components/`, `hooks/`, etc. (outside `features/`) exist exclusively to share code between features of the same module.
- They are still internal to the module and must not be imported by other modules.

### 6. The module `index.ts` assembles the public API
- The module's root `index.ts` re-exports only what other modules are allowed to consume.
- It may import from feature `index.ts` files or from module-level layers.
- It never imports internal feature paths directly.

### 7. State ownership follows the same rule
- Feature-specific state lives in `features/<feature>/store/`.
- State shared across features of the same module lives in `modules/<domain>/store/`.
- State shared across modules is exposed through the module's public API, never by sharing slices directly.

## Naming Conventions

| Item | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Feature folder | kebab-case verb/noun | `login`, `reset-password`, `apply-coupon` |
| Component | PascalCase | `LoginForm.tsx`, `ResetPasswordPage.tsx` |
| Hook | camelCase `use` prefix | `useLogin.ts`, `useResetPassword.ts` |
| Service | camelCase | `loginService.ts`, `resetPasswordService.ts` |
| Type file | camelCase `.types.ts` suffix | `login.types.ts` |
| Store file | camelCase `.store.ts` suffix | `login.store.ts` |

## Decision Tree — Where Does This File Go?

```
Is it used by only one feature?
  └─ Yes → place it inside features/<feature>/<layer>/

Is it used by more than one feature within the same module?
  └─ Yes → promote it to modules/<domain>/<layer>/

Is it used by more than one module?
  └─ Yes → promote it to shared/
           (only if it has no domain-specific logic)
```

## What to Check on Architecture Changes

When adding or changing a feature, verify:

- [ ] The feature folder is named after a user-facing action or capability
- [ ] There is no `components/` or `hooks/` folder inside the feature — use `sessions/` instead
- [ ] Each session with logic has exactly `use<Name>.ts` and `<Name>.tsx`; pure layout shells have only `<Name>.tsx`
- [ ] No `index.ts` barrel exists inside any session folder
- [ ] No sibling feature is imported directly
- [ ] Shared intra-module code lives at the module level, not duplicated in features
- [ ] `features/<feature>/index.ts` exports the assembled page — not raw sessions or hooks
- [ ] `modules/<domain>/index.ts` exports only what other modules need
- [ ] Any type used by more than one feature has been promoted to `modules/<domain>/types/` — not duplicated
- [ ] Any type used by more than one module has been promoted to `shared/types/` — not duplicated

## Examples

**Correct**
```ts
// modules/auth/features/login/sessions/LoginForm/useLoginForm.ts
import { authApiClient } from 'modules/auth/services/authApiClient'
import { AuthUser } from 'modules/auth/types/auth.types'

// modules/auth/features/login/index.ts — assembled page only
export function LoginPage() { ... }

// modules/auth/index.ts
export { LoginPage } from './features/login'
```

**Wrong**
```ts
// Import sibling feature sessions ✗
// Export raw LoginForm from feature index instead of assembled page ✗
// useState in .tsx presentation instead of hook ✗
```
